sec.p:
Our new philodanid species is remarkable in its geographical isolation from P. johnstoni . Afrophilodana is from montane tropical Kenya , but P. johnstoni is from Michigan, a cool temperate region of the U.S. A, although unusual, this disjunct distribution is also similar to Micromegistus ( Parantennulidae ), found on carabid beetles in New Zealand , Australia and North and South America (
Womersley 1958 ;
Hamilton-Smith 1967 ;
Nickel & Elzinga 1970 ; OS pers. obs.). Afrophilodana is the first record of this superfamily from Africa. We expect that these disjunct distributions are an artifact of little collecting for these unusual mites.
